In terms of other offensive players:

Purdys average passing yards is much higher than any other player. This makes sense as he is the quarterback so he always starts with the ball and typically looks to pass. When he doesnt pass he rushes, and his average rushing yards is in line with or greater than that of the other offensive players with the exception of Breece Hall whose average rushing yards is over three times that of the next closest player. Similarly, Purdys average pssing touchdowns and interceptions are higher than those of the other offensive players. This is another result of him being quarterback and passing much more than any other player.

defBio <- inner_join(defClean, bioClean, by = 'Name') %>% group_by(Position) %>% summarize(total_solo_tackles = sum(Tackles_Solo), total_tackles_assist = sum(Tackles_ASST), total_sacks = sum(Tackles_Sack))
